00:00:34.308 --> 00:00:35.570
- Good afternoon, I'm William Lester,

00:00:35.570 --> 00:00:38.560
professor of chemistry
and chair of the Hitchcock

00:00:38.560 --> 00:00:40.180
Professorship Committee.

00:00:40.180 --> 00:00:42.760
On behalf of the Hitchcock Professorship,

00:00:42.760 --> 00:00:45.260
we're pleased to welcome Sir John Gurdon

00:00:45.260 --> 00:00:47.500
as this year's speaker in the Charles M.

00:00:47.500 --> 00:00:50.610
and Martha Hitchcock Lecture Series.

00:00:50.610 --> 00:00:52.770
So John Gurdon's groundbreaking studies

00:00:52.770 --> 00:00:55.830
in nuclear transplantation
galvanized effort

00:00:55.830 --> 00:00:57.970
to clone a mammal from an adult cell,

00:00:57.970 --> 00:01:01.883
a quest that in 1996 produced
a healthy sheep named Dolly.

00:01:03.020 --> 00:01:05.270
The intellectual driving
force behind this success

00:01:05.270 --> 00:01:08.210
was Gurdon's discovery
that cells of the body

00:01:08.210 --> 00:01:11.410
are capable of differentiating
into all cell types

00:01:11.410 --> 00:01:12.683
of the vertebrate animal.

00:01:14.050 --> 00:01:15.720
Gurdon provided unprecedented evidence

00:01:15.720 --> 00:01:19.220
that nuclear transplantations
from specialized cells

00:01:19.220 --> 00:01:22.430
could give rise to adult, fertile

00:01:22.430 --> 00:01:24.463
genetic copies of their donor.

00:01:25.300 --> 00:01:28.000
His findings also yielded wide-ranging

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:29.490
medical implications for the use

00:01:29.490 --> 00:01:31.890
of stem cells in tissue therapy.

00:01:31.890 --> 00:01:33.660
Gurdon recently revisited this field

00:01:33.660 --> 00:01:36.420
to study nuclear
reprogramming and cell fate

00:01:36.420 --> 00:01:39.360
determination in amphibians.

00:01:39.360 --> 00:01:43.800
Gurdon was born on October 2nd, 1933,

00:01:43.800 --> 00:01:46.720
in Dippenhall, England, and
entered Christ Church College

00:01:46.720 --> 00:01:50.160
at Oxford University
intending to study Classics.

00:01:50.160 --> 00:01:52.500
He transferred to the
Department of Zoology,

00:01:52.500 --> 00:01:55.233
earning his PhD in embryology in 1960.

00:01:57.210 --> 00:01:59.500
Following postdoctoral
work at the California

00:01:59.500 --> 00:02:02.460
Institute of Technology,
and a six-month sabbatical

00:02:02.460 --> 00:02:04.990
at the Carnegie Institution in Baltimore,

00:02:04.990 --> 00:02:09.240
in 1965 Gurdon returned
to Oxford University.

00:02:09.240 --> 00:02:12.860
In 1971 he moved to the
Medical Research Council's

00:02:12.860 --> 00:02:15.750
laboratory of molecular
biology in Cambridge,

00:02:15.750 --> 00:02:19.660
subsequently becoming head
of the Cell Biology Division.

00:02:19.660 --> 00:02:22.720
He was appointed professor of cell biology

00:02:22.720 --> 00:02:25.350
in the University of Cambridge in 1983,

00:02:25.350 --> 00:02:28.070
and served as master of
Magdalene College Cambridge

00:02:28.070 --> 00:02:30.100
from 1995 to 2002.

00:02:32.049 --> 00:02:34.850
Gurdon is an active researcher
at the Wellcome Trust

00:02:34.850 --> 00:02:39.770
Cancer Research UK Gurdon
Institute of Cancer

00:02:39.770 --> 00:02:43.210
and Developmental Biology,
and served as its first

00:02:43.210 --> 00:02:46.223
chairman from 1988 to 2001.

00:02:47.100 --> 00:02:50.070
Sir John Gurdon's
international awards and honors

00:02:51.155 --> 00:02:53.420
include the Albert Bechet Prize
of the Belgian Royal Academy

00:02:53.420 --> 00:02:58.420
in 1968; the Royal Medal in
1985; and the Copley Medal

00:02:59.310 --> 00:03:03.470
in 2003 of the Royal Society of London;

00:03:03.470 --> 00:03:08.070
International Prize for
Biology from Japan, 1987;

00:03:08.070 --> 00:03:12.150
